Try this:

source ~/setup_cantera
ctnew -f90
make -f demo.mak

This will build a demo Fortran 90 Cantera program.  If this works, you 
can use demo.f90 as a starting point to develop your program.  If it 
doesn&#39;t, then some compile flags are not being set correctly for your 
Fortran compiler.  You may need to play with options in &#39;configure.&#39;  
The configure script will detect if you are using the Absoft or NAG 
Fortran compiler, and set the compile flags correctly, but for other 
compilers you will have to do it yourself. Specify that the names of 
object files should be lower case with a trailing underscore, and 
specify the directory where module files may be found (e.g. 
/usr/local/include/cantera).  Also, be sure that the Fortran compiler 
produces object files compatible with the ones produced by the C++ 
compiler you use to build Cantera.

